o each other\n- relationship_strength: an integer score between 1 to 10, indicating strength of the relationship between the source entity and target entity\nFormat each relationship as (\"relationship\"<|><source_entity><|><target_entity><|><relationship_description><|><relationship_strength>)\n\n3. Return output in English as a single list of all the entities and relationships identified in steps 1 and 2. Use **##** as the list delimiter.\n\n4. If you have to translate into English, just translate the descriptions, nothing else!\n\n5. When finished, output <|COMPLETE|>.\n\n-Examples-\n######################\n\nExample 1:\n\nentity_types: [publisher, author, editor, peer reviewer, AI technology, journal, policy, guideline, organization, tool, algorithm, copyright, transparency, accountability, ethical use, authorship, publication process, peer review process, manuscript, content, data, research, integrity, originality, plagiarism, bias, inaccuracy, hallucination, language model, generative AI, LLM, copyright holder, editorial decision, submission, disclosure, rights protection, confidentiality, privacy, compliance, citation, source, manuscript preparation, research design, academic publishing, AI policy]\ntext:\n.\nPublishers should take steps to be transparent about which of their publishing processes or workflows are automated, and where AI decisions are involved. Any AI powered automation should be clearly presented to the relevant participants of the peer review process—authors, reviewers, or editors—with clarification on how the algorithm provided the result or conclusion.\nFor authors\nAuthors can challenge an editorial decision, if they have a valid reason, in accordance with the journal’s standard procedures. Challenging an editorial decision that was made by AI or based on an AI recommendation should follow the same process as any editorial decision made by a human. Whether the decision was made by AI or a human editor, the journal and publisher are acco